<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(3)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Audit committee financial expert </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_17"></A>Finance and Audit Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our
F&amp;A Committee, which consists entirely of independent directors, held six meetings in 2016. Additionally, the F&amp;A Committee held joint meetings with the Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology Committee during each of the quarterly Risk&nbsp;&amp;
Technology Committee meetings, meeting four times during 2016 to discuss matters relating to the overlap between risk and internal control functions. The F&amp;A Committee also met in private session with the Chief Executive Officer, Chief Financial
Officer, General Counsel, Chief Risk Officer, Director of Internal Audit and PwC during various meetings held during 2016. The F&amp;A Committee of the Board of Directors assists the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in fulfilling its oversight of
(1)&nbsp;the integrity of the financial statements and its risk and control environment, (2)&nbsp;the qualification and independence of, and relationship with, the independent registered public accounting firm, (3)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s internal
audit function, (4)&nbsp;compliance with applicable legal and regulatory requirements and (5)&nbsp;compliance with the Company&#146;s Code of Business Conduct and Ethics. The F&amp;A Committee also reviews and makes recommendations to the Board
regarding (1)&nbsp;any proposed material capital formation plans, including planned issuances of equity securities and debt instruments, and stock repurchase programs and (2)&nbsp;certain acquisitions, investments, new business ventures and
divestitures by the Company. The F&amp;A Committee annually reviews and approves the Company&#146;s (1)&nbsp;treasury investment policy outlining the general investment objectives of the Company and the specific instruments for which investments are
permitted, (2)&nbsp;liquidity risk management policy and (3)&nbsp;contingency funding plan. The F&amp;A Committee also annually prepares a report to the Board of Directors regarding the performance of the F&amp;A Committee&#146;s duties and
responsibilities, including its oversight of the independent registered public accounting firm and of management&#146;s preparation of the Company&#146;s financial statements, which is included in the Company&#146;s annual proxy statement. See
&#147;Report of the Finance and Audit Committee&#148; beginning on page 51. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our F&amp;A Committee has direct
responsibility for the appointment, compensation, evaluation, retention and oversight of the work of the independent registered public accounting firm, which has been engaged to prepare </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-13-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
an audit report or to perform other audit, review or attest services for or on behalf of the Company. The F&amp;A Committee is responsible for the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of all audit and permitted <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services performed by our independent registered public accounting firm. The independent registered public accounting
firm reports directly to the F&amp;A Committee. The F&amp;A Committee&#146;s function is one of oversight, recognizing that our management is responsible for preparing our financial statements, and our independent registered public accounting firm
is responsible for auditing those statements. Annually, the F&amp;A Committee evaluates the independent registered public accounting firm and, as appropriate, recommends that our Board request stockholder ratification of the appointment of the
independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee also acts on behalf of our Board in
monitoring and overseeing the performance of our internal audit function. At least annually, the F&amp;A Committee reviews the organizational structure, qualifications, independence and performance of this function and the scope of its planned
activities. The F&amp;A Committee also oversees the operation of a comprehensive system of internal controls covering the integrity of our financial statements and reports, compliance with laws, regulations and corporate policies. See &#147;Board
Oversight of Risk&#148; beginning on page 10 above for additional discussion of the F&amp;A Committee&#146;s duties and responsibilities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Board of Directors has determined that the F&amp;A Committee consists entirely of directors who meet the independence requirements of the listing standards of the NYSE and Rule <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10A-3</FONT> under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the &#147;Exchange Act&#148;). Our Board has also determined that all members of its F&amp;A Committee are financially literate and have accounting or
related financial management expertise within the meaning of the NYSE listing standards as interpreted by our Board. Our Board has determined in its business judgment that Mr.&nbsp;Schmitt satisfies the definition of &#147;audit committee financial
expert&#148; as set out in the rules and regulations under the Exchange Act, based upon his experience actively supervising a principal accounting or financial officer or public accountant. The SEC provides that an &#147;audit committee financial
expert&#148; does not have additional duties, obligations or liabilities and is not considered an expert under the Securities Act of 1933, as amended (the &#147;Securities Act&#148;). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_18"></A>Nominating and Corporate Governance Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our N&amp;CG Committee, which consists entirely of independent directors, held one meeting in 2016. Subject to our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">By-Laws,</FONT> the N&amp;CG Committee is responsible
for identifying individuals qualified to become Board members consistent with the criteria included in the N&amp;CG charter and our Corporate Governance Guidelines, including candidates recommended by stockholders in compliance with procedures set
forth in the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">By-Laws,</FONT> and to recommend that the Board select these individuals as nominees for election to the Board. Stockholders who wish to nominate directors directly at an annual meeting in accordance
with the procedures in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">By-Laws</FONT> should follow the instructions in the section entitled &#147;Stockholder Proposals for 2018 Annual Meeting&#148; on page 63. Other functions of the N&amp;CG Committee include
(1)&nbsp;recommending the size of, and directors to serve on, committees of the Board, (2)&nbsp;advising the Board with respect to matters of Board composition and procedures, (3)&nbsp;developing and recommending to the Board a set of corporate
governance principles applicable to the Company and overseeing corporate governance matters generally and (4)&nbsp;overseeing the annual evaluation of our management and the Board. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_19"></A>Compensation Committee </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our
Compensation Committee, which consists entirely of independent directors, held nine meetings in 2016. The Compensation Committee operates under a written charter adopted by the Board, and pursuant to its charter, the Compensation Committee has
responsibility for evaluating and approving annually all compensation awarded to the Company&#146;s executive officers, including the named executive officers (&#147;NEOs&#148;). In addition to administering the Company&#146;s equity-based plans,
including reviewing and approving equity grants to executive officers, and the Company&#146;s deferred cash compensation program, the Compensation Committee has general oversight of the incentive compensation plans, policies and programs of the
Company and its subsidiaries. The </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-14-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
Compensation Committee also evaluates the performance of our CEO, and, based on such evaluation, reviews and approves his annual salary, cash incentive bonus and long-term equity incentive bonus.
The Compensation Committee is responsible for producing an annual report on executive compensation and assisting management in the preparation of the Compensation Discussion and Analysis included herein. Additionally, the Compensation Committee
retains its own independent compensation consultant who from time to time provides advice to the Compensation Committee on executive compensation matters and has the authority to obtain advice and assistance from internal or external legal,
accounting and other advisors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee also provides assistance to the Board of Directors
by setting performance-based compensation criteria for our CEO and other key executives, certifying the results of such performance at the end of the annual performance period and, after evaluating these results as compared to the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-established</FONT> performance criteria, determining the amount of such performance-based compensation that is awarded to the CEO and other key executives (including, as noted above, the amount and type of equity
awards granted to this population). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_20"></A>Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology Committee </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology Committee held five meetings in 2016. Additionally, the Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology
Committee held joint meetings with the F&amp;A Committee during each of the quarterly Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology Committee meetings, meeting four times during 2016. The primary purpose of the Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology Committee is to assist the
Board in its oversight responsibilities relating to the identification, monitoring and assessment of the key risks of the Company, including the significant policies, procedures and practices employed in risk management (including technology risk
management). See &#147;Board Oversight of Risk&#148; beginning on page 10 above for a discussion of the Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology Committee&#146;s duties and responsibilities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_21"></A>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION CONSULTANT </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>TO THE
COMPENSATION COMMITTEE </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As mentioned above, the Compensation Committee retains the services of a qualified
independent compensation consultant that possesses the necessary skill, experiences and resources to meet the Compensation Committee&#146;s needs, and that provides services solely to the Compensation Committee and not to the Company. Following the
closing of the Mergers, the Compensation Committee engaged Pay Governance LLC (&#147;Pay Governance&#148;), to serve as its independent compensation consultant. Prior to being engaged by the Compensation Committee, Pay Governance advised the
Compensation Committees of both GETCO and Knight and, consequently, was well positioned to advise the Compensation Committee on executive compensation design following the closing of the Mergers. During this period, Pay Governance assisted the
Compensation Committee in collecting and evaluating external data regarding executive compensation and advised the Compensation Committee on developing trends and best practices in executive compensation design. Given the extent of Pay
Governance&#146;s involvement with respect to establishing the Company&#146;s executive compensation framework in connection with the Mergers, the Compensation Committee has since retained Pay Governance to continue to counsel the Compensation
Committee on an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">as-needed</FONT> basis. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee has
determined that Pay Governance had no conflict of interest in providing services to the Compensation Committee and was independent for purposes of the NYSE requirements regarding the independence of compensation consultants. In accordance with SEC
and NYSE requirements, the Compensation Committee reached this conclusion based on an evaluation of such factors including, among others, that (1)&nbsp;Pay Governance provides services only to the Compensation Committee and not to the Company,
(2)&nbsp;Pay Governance does not have any significant business or personal relationship with any member of the Compensation Committee or any executive officer of the Company and (3)&nbsp;the fees paid by the Compensation Committee to Pay Governance
are not material to Pay Governance&#146;s total revenues. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-15-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_22"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE INTERLOCKS AND INSIDER PARTICIPATION
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">None of the members of the KCG Compensation Committee have any relationships that would create a
Compensation Committee interlock as defined under applicable SEC regulation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_23"></A>BOARD EVALUATION
AND EDUCATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each year, our Board and our F&amp;A, N&amp;CG, Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology and Compensation
Committees evaluate their effectiveness. Our Board views self-evaluation as an ongoing process designed to achieve high levels of Board and committee performance. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2016, our Board participated in Board information sessions during regularly scheduled and special meetings. During
these sessions, directors received business updates from senior management, risk executives and our General Counsel. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Board also encourages directors to participate in continuing director education programs and our Company reimburses directors for the expenses of this participation. Additionally, new directors are
required to participate in our director orientation program in their first six months as a director. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_24">
</A>CONTACTING THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Interested parties may send communications to our Board or our
independent directors or any Board committee by mail. Correspondence should be addressed to the Board of Directors or any such individual director or group or Board committee members by either name or title. The correspondence should be sent to
Corporate Secretary at KCG Holdings, Inc., 300 Vesey Street, New York, NY 10282. To communicate with any of our directors electronically, stockholders or interested parties may send an electronic message to <U>kcgboard@kcg.com</U>. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">All communications received as set forth in the preceding paragraph will be opened by our General Counsel (or his
designee) for the sole purpose of determining whether the contents represent a message to our directors. Any contents that are not in the nature of advertising, promotions of a product or service, or patently offensive material will be forwarded
promptly to the addressee. In the case of communications to the Board or any group of directors or Board committee members, our General Counsel will make sufficient copies of the contents to send to each director who is a member of the group or
committee to which the envelope or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">e-mail</FONT> is addressed. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-16-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_25"></A>COMPENSATION OF DIRECTORS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_26"></A>Director Compensation </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Upon recommendation from the Compensation Committee, the Board of Directors adopted a director compensation policy in 2013 that establishes the framework for compensating the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> members of the Board of Directors for their service to the Company. Under this director compensation policy, upon commencing service on the Board, new
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors are awarded an initial grant of restricted stock units (&#147;RSUs&#148;) with an aggregate grant date fair value of $80,000. Continuing directors receive, on the first business day
after the annual meeting of stockholders, an annual grant of RSUs with an aggregate grant date fair value of $80,000. Continuing directors are also paid, on the first business day after the annual meeting of stockholders, an annual cash retainer of
$80,000, which will cover the period until the following annual meeting of stockholders. The annual cash retainer is prorated for new directors who join between annual meetings of stockholders. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Committee chairs will receive an additional $20,000 annual cash retainer. Committee members do not receive any additional
membership fees, but are paid $1,000 for each committee meeting in which they participate. Under the director compensation policy, directors do not receive any fees for attending Board of Directors meetings. Directors are required to own stock with
a value equal to three times the annual cash retainer ($240,000) within five years from the time the director joins the Board of Directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Board of Directors established Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman&#146;s compensation package outside of the director compensation policy given the additional contributions expected of him as <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Executive</FONT> Chairman of the Board of Directors (such as providing strategic guidance and feedback to our CEO and Board of Directors, maintaining regular interaction with senior management between Board of
Directors meetings and regularly spending time at KCG&#146;s offices). In consideration for Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman&#146;s service as <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Executive</FONT> Chairman he was granted RSUs with an aggregate grant date value of
$320,000 on the first business day after the annual meeting of stockholders in May 2016. All RSUs granted to <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors have a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> vesting period and
provide for forfeiture in the event a director leaves before the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> anniversary of the grant date (except in the event of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-renewal</FONT> of term (if the director
serves the remainder of his or her current term), retirement, death or disability). All directors are reimbursed for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">out-of-pocket</FONT></FONT> expenses incurred in the performance
of their services for KCG. KCG also extends coverage to directors under its directors&#146; and officers&#146; indemnity insurance policies. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_27"></A>2016 Director Compensation Table </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table provides information concerning the compensation of each
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director who served in 2016. Mr.&nbsp;Coleman did not receive any compensation for his service as a director. Messrs. Fisher, Smith and Weller and Ms.&nbsp;Tookes were elected to the Board of
Directors on January&nbsp;18, 2017, and therefore did not serve or receive compensation in 2016. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On May&nbsp;12, 2016, the day following the 2016 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, each <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director
then serving on the Board, except for Messrs. Haldeman and Kern, was awarded an annual cash retainer of $80,000. Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman does not receive the annual cash retainer pursuant to the terms of the director compensation policy. Mr.&nbsp;Kern
waived the right to receive any cash compensation for his service on the Board of Directors and any committees thereof. Amounts included in this column also represent cash retainers paid for service as a committee chair and cash paid for attendance
at committee meetings. Mr.&nbsp;Morris waived the right to receive any cash compensation for his service on the Board of Directors and any committees thereof prior to the 2016 Annual Meeting of Stockholders, and he therefore waived all fees earned
for his attendance at committee meetings prior to the 2016 Annual Meeting. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On May&nbsp;12, 2016, each <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> director then serving on the Board, except for Messrs. Haldeman and
Kern, was granted an award of 6,089 RSUs with an aggregate grant date fair value of $80,000. On May&nbsp;12, 2016, Mr.&nbsp;Haldeman was granted an award of 24,354 RSUs with an aggregate grant date fair value of $320,000. Mr.&nbsp;Kern waived the
right to receive any RSU awards as compensation for his service on the Board of Directors and any committees thereof. The aggregate grant date fair value of the annual RSUs granted to the other <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT>
directors on May&nbsp;12, 2016 is based on $13.14, the average of the high and low price of a share of KCG Common Stock as quoted on the NYSE on the date preceding the date of grant. Each RSU will vest one year from the date of grant or upon earlier
retirement (age 72 as set forth in our Corporate Governance Guidelines) and will be settled in shares of KCG Common Stock upon vesting. Amount shown represents the aggregate grant date fair value computed in accordance with Financial Accounting
Standards Board&#146;s Accounting Standards Codification 718 Compensation-Stock Compensation (&#147;FASB ASC Topic 718&#148;). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_28"></A>COMPENSATION AND RISK </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">KCG designs its compensation policies and practices in a way to support a strong risk management culture. KCG&#146;s
compensation program is designed to encourage its executive officers and employees to focus on KCG&#146;s short-term and long-term performance without incentivizing unnecessary or excessive risk-taking. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our KCG Holdings, Inc. Amended and Restated Equity Incentive Plan (our &#147;Equity Incentive Plan&#148;), which was most
recently approved at the annual meeting of stockholders held on May&nbsp;12, 2015, provides that, if at any time within two years after the date on which an employee exercises an option or stock appreciation award (&#147;SAR&#148;) or on which
restricted stock or RSUs vest (each, a &#147;Realization Event&#148;), the employee is (1)&nbsp;terminated for cause, (2)&nbsp;engages or has engaged in any activity that is in violation of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT>
agreement, (3)&nbsp;violates or has violated any confidential or proprietary information obligation the employee owes to KCG (including, but not limited to, obligations in any <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-compete</FONT> agreement, employment
agreement, offer letter, employee handbook, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-disclosure</FONT> agreement, Code of Business Conduct or Ethics, equity award agreement or any other Company agreement signed by the employee that contains such
obligations) and/or (4)&nbsp;engages in or has engaged in any act of fraud against KCG, the Compensation Committee may require the employee to pay to KCG an amount equal to the gain he or she recognized from the Realization Event, determined on a
gross basis, without reduction for taxes incurred and without regard to any subsequent change in the fair market value of a share of KCG Common Stock. The Company also may cancel or adjust any award granted under the Equity Incentive Plan if
KCG&#146;s financial statements on which the calculation of the award was based are subsequently restated, and the Compensation Committee determines that such restated financial statements would have resulted in a smaller award, or no award, if such
information had been known at the time the award was originally calculated. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition, in July 2013 the
Board adopted a Compensation Recoupment Policy to maintain and enhance a culture that is focused on integrity and accountability and that discourages conduct detrimental to the Company&#146;s sustainable growth. The Compensation Recoupment Policy
provides that, in the event that the Company restates its financial statements, the Compensation Committee may recoup from any executive officer the annual bonuses (regardless of whether such bonuses were paid or awarded in cash, equity or a
combination thereof) earned during the three-year period preceding the date on which the Company files restated financial statements with the SEC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee believes that mitigating excessive risk taking is an important component of the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy. Accordingly, as part of the Compensation Committee&#146;s
oversight of the Company&#146;s executive compensation plans and practices, it considers factors such as the balance of fixed compensation and discretionary compensation, the balance of short-term and long-term incentives, and appropriate
risk-mitigating controls such as the Equity Incentive Plan&#146;s recapture and cancellation provisions and the Compensation Recoupment Policy, to ensure that the Company&#146;s compensation framework is structured in a way that aligns with sound
risk management and that does not create risks that are reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on the Company. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-19-
</FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Head of Global Execution Services and

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For selected biographical information with respect to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman, please refer
above to the biographical information of our directors. Selected biographical information with respect to the other executive officers is set forth below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Philip Allison</I></B> (41), Chief Executive Officer, KCG Europe Limited (&#147;KCG Europe&#148;) since September&nbsp;22, 2014, leads the operations and strategic direction for KCG&#146;s
agency-execution and market making businesses in Europe, as well as certain U.S.-based market making businesses. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Allison spent 17 years at UBS Group AG, most recently as Global Head of Cash Equities and EMEA Head of Equities,
responsible for operations across more than 30 countries. Mr.&nbsp;Allison began his career at UBS in 1997 trading derivatives and index arbitrage strategies in the UK and, later, ETFs in the U.S. In 2002, Mr.&nbsp;Allison became responsible for
global statistical proprietary trading and client algorithmic trading in Europe. Mr.&nbsp;Allison expanded his responsibilities in 2006 to include automated market making and statistical model development for global cash equities. UBS appointed
Mr.&nbsp;Allison the Head of European Client Trading and Execution in 2008, responsible for cash, sales, portfolio and electronic trading in the region. In 2010 he became Global Head of Cash Equities, and additionally in March 2012, EMEA Head of
Equities, serving on the boards of UBS Ltd and the Association for Financial Markets in Europe. Mr.&nbsp;Allison has a degree in mathematics from Cambridge University. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Michael Blum </I></B>(49), Chief Technology Officer since October&nbsp;1, 2016, is responsible for all of
KCG&#146;s technology operations and infrastructure. Prior to joining KCG, Mr.&nbsp;Blum was the Chief Technology Officer of Teza Technologies and was responsible for managing its full software, network and infrastructure technology stack. He also
previously worked at GETCO as the global head of client execution services, and was responsible for leading GETCO&#146;s client-facing units. Prior to that, Mr.&nbsp;Blum was a managing director at UBS Investment Bank where he served as global head
of client facing technology. At UBS, he was responsible for UBS&#146;s Pinpoint EMS, Fusion website and the core technology behind UBS&#146;s global OMS, smart router, and ATS. Prior to UBS, Mr.&nbsp;Blum served as vice president of development at
ISLAND ECN where he was responsible for the design and development of Island&#146;s edge technology. Mr.&nbsp;Blum started his career in the industry as a developer at ATD, one of the first electronic market makers in the industry. Mr.&nbsp;Blum has
a degree in computer science from the University of Dayton. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>John McCarthy</I></B> (53), General Counsel
and Corporate Secretary since the closing of the Mergers on July&nbsp;1, 2013, focuses on a broad range of global corporate and regulatory matters for KCG. Previously, Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy was General Counsel of GETCO, which he joined in 2006, through
the closing of the Mergers. Prior to 2006, Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy served as associate director at the Securities and Exchange Commission, where he led the Office </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-20-
</FONT></P>

SEC, Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy clerked for the Court of Special Appeals of Maryland. Mr.&nbsp;McCarthy earned a B.S. in Engineering and an A.B. in Economics from the University of Michigan, an M.Sc. in Finance from the London School of Economics and a J.D.
with Honors from the University of Maryland. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Nick Ogurtsov</I></B> (39), Chief Risk Officer since the
closing of the Mergers and Chief Operating Officer since August&nbsp;16, 2013, has more than 16 years of experience in leadership and financial markets. As Chief Operating Officer, he is responsible for overseeing KCG&#146;s operations and clearing.
As Chief Risk Officer, he is responsible for managing KCG&#146;s strategic and operational risk management framework, including the design and implementation of systems and processes to identify, mitigate and access KCG&#146;s risk exposure.
Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov was the Chief Risk Officer of GETCO until the closing of the Mergers. Prior to joining GETCO in 2012, Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov was Managing Director and Global Head of UBS&#146;s high-frequency electronic trading group, EMM
Group. He built and managed EMM Group&#146;s global team in New York, London and Tokyo, where they traded equities, fixed income and foreign exchange. As a member UBS&#146;s management team for the global cash equities business, Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov
also helped rebuild UBS&#146;s trading technology in the Asia-Pacific region. He began his career at SBC Warburg (subsequently merged into UBS) as a convertible bonds trader and later <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">co-headed</FONT> the
equity-linked structured products team. Mr.&nbsp;Ogurtsov received a B.S. in Physics and Computer Science from Beloit College and a Master&#146;s degree in Computer Science from the University of Arizona. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Steffen Parratt</I></B> (54), Chief Financial Officer since January&nbsp;6, 2015, is responsible for all financial
aspects of KCG. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt has more than 20 years of leadership experience in financial services, technology and corporate strategy. Prior to becoming Chief Financial Officer of KCG, Mr.&nbsp;Parratt was an entrepreneur. During this time, he
launched ventures in finance, management, and strategy, with a focus on developing software to realize operational effectiveness and efficiencies. Previously, he was a Managing Director at Bank of America Merrill Lynch, where he helped develop a
strategic plan to integrate Merrill Lynch, U.S. Trust and the legacy Bank of America wealth business. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt also spent more than a decade at Citigroup Inc. in a number of management roles, most recently as Managing Director and Global
Staff Functions Task Leader, Reengineering and Productivity Group, where he was responsible for reengineering organizations and processes in the firm&#146;s finance, risk, compliance, audit, legal, human resources units. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt began his
career as an engineer, and held positions at Sandia National Laboratories and Hughes Aircraft Company. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt received an M.B.A. in Finance from The Wharton School. He received a Ph.D. and M.Sc. in Engineering from Cornell University. He
earned his B.Sc. in Mechanical Engineering and a M.Sc. in Electrical Engineering from the University of Rochester. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Ryan Primmer</I></B> (47), Global Head of Quantitative and Systematic Trading, and previously Global Head of Fixed Income, Foreign Exchange and Commodities Trading from August 2013, currently
oversees quantitative and systematic trading strategies for KCG. Mr.&nbsp;Primmer joined KCG in August 2013 after more than 21 years at UBS and its predecessor firms. He began his career in 1991 at O&#146;Connor&nbsp;&amp; Associates in Chicago,
Illinois, a market making firm focused on equity options, working as an options trader and market maker. Mr.&nbsp;Primmer transitioned to trading convertible bonds and eventually spent time in London and New York where he was <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">co-head</FONT> of trading for the convertible bond desk. From 1999 to 2004, he led the expansion of the U.S. program and quantitative trading business. From 2004 to 2008, Mr.&nbsp;Primmer was UBS&#146;s head of trading for
U.S. equities until he was appointed during the financial crisis to lead the efforts to dissolve the company&#146;s mortgage asset portfolios and help establish and lead the UBS&#146;s fund management team for StabFund. From 2009 to 2012,
Mr.&nbsp;Primmer was Global Head of Equities Proprietary Trading at UBS, overseeing fundamental and statistical strategies. Just prior to joining KCG, he was Global Head of Equities Trading at UBS. Mr.&nbsp;Primmer received a B.A. in Economics from
Lawrence University in Appleton, Wisconsin. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Greg Tusar </I></B>(48), Head of Global Execution Services
and Platforms since August 2013, is responsible for KCG&#146;s sales, products and platforms globally. Mr.&nbsp;Tusar joined KCG in August 2013 from Goldman Sachs, where he spent 13 years, most recently as a partner and global head of the
firm&#146;s equities electronic trading </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-21-

<TR BGCOLOR="#cceeff" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_31"></A>PROPOSAL 2&#151;ADVISORY APPROVAL OF</B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>2016 COMPENSATION OF NAMED EXECUTIVE OFFICERS</B></FONT></P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act requires public companies
to provide their stockholders with an advisory vote to approve executive compensation at least once every three years. We are providing this stockholder advisory vote on the executive compensation of our named executive officers in accordance with
Section 14A of the Exchange Act and Exchange Act Rule <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">14a-21(a).</FONT> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This
proposal, commonly known as a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;Say-on-Pay&#148;</FONT></FONT> proposal, gives stockholders the opportunity to endorse or not endorse our executive pay program and policies. At
the annual meeting of Knight stockholders in 2011 and as the successor to Knight, starting with our 2013 annual meeting of stockholders, we have provided stockholders with an advisory vote on our executive compensation on an annual basis, and at
this meeting our stockholders will be given an opportunity under Proposal 3 to vote on an advisory basis to determine the future frequency of our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> votes.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_32"></A>Background </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Board values our stockholders&#146; feedback and pays careful attention to communications from our stockholders regarding the Company&#146;s executive compensation practices. Our executive
compensation program is designed to pay for performance and to align the long-term interests of our named executive officers and other members of our management team with the long-term interests of our stockholders, as discussed in more detail
throughout this Proxy Statement. We believe these design and alignment principles help to ensure an appropriate balance between risk and reward; while our incentive compensation arrangements do not encourage employees to take unnecessary or
excessive risks, our employees are rewarded for executing on the Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives. Further, the Compensation Committee and the Board of Directors believe that the compensation policies and procedures articulated in
this Proxy Statement are effective in furthering KCG&#146;s achievement of short-term and long-term business goals, and that the compensation of our named executive officers reported in this Proxy Statement, which is structured to motivate superior
individual performance, has supported and contributed to KCG&#146;s success. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">At our 2016 Annual Meeting of
Stockholders, our advisory vote to approve named executive officer compensation received the strong support of our stockholders (approximately 97% of votes cast). Our approach to compensation continues to be designed to directly link pay to
performance, balance corporate, strategic and individual objectives, appropriately balance risk and reward and to align the long-term interests of our executives with those of our stockholders. We encourage you to review the Compensation Discussion
and Analysis and the related tables and narrative disclosure starting on page 26 for additional information regarding our key compensation practice and philosophies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_33"></A>2016 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> Advisory Vote </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In accordance with Section 14A of the Exchange Act, we are asking our stockholders to vote on the resolution set forth
below. Your vote on this resolution is an advisory vote. Although the Compensation Committee is not required by law to take any action in response to the stockholder vote, it intends to evaluate the results of the vote carefully when making future
decisions regarding compensation of the named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_34"></A>Resolution </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We are asking our stockholders to vote on the following resolution: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">RESOLVED, that the stockholders approve the 2016 compensation of the named executive officers, as disclosed in this Proxy
Statement pursuant to Item 402 of Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> including the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#148; the compensation tables and related disclosure. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-23-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_35"></A>Recommendation of the Board </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that you vote &#147;<U>FOR</U>&#148; the approval of the 2016
compensation of our named executive officers, as disclosed in this Proxy Statement.</B> </FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_36"></A>PROPOSAL 3&#151;ADVISORY APPROVAL OF FREQUENCY OF THE ADVISORY
STOCKHOLDER VOTE TO APPROVE NAMED EXECUTIVE OFFICER COMPENSATION</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> advisory vote in Proposal 2 above, under Exchange Act rules, you have an opportunity to vote on an advisory basis on the frequency of <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> votes going forward&#151;specifically, whether <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> votes should be done every
year, every two years or every three years. We are providing this stockholder advisory vote on the frequency of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> votes in accordance with Section 14A of the
Exchange Act and Exchange Act Rule <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">14a-21(b).</FONT> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_37"></A>Background
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">At the 2011 annual meeting of Knight stockholders, the Knight Board of Directors recommended the option of
holding a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> vote every year and approximately 90% of the votes cast voted in favor of holding such a vote annually. As the successor to Knight, we have held an
advisory <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> vote each year since 2013. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our Board believes that an annual vote fosters communication between our stockholders, the Board and the Compensation Committee and offers an effective way for stockholders to provide ongoing input on
executive compensation, as well as the Company&#146;s compensation practices and policies. The Board believes that an annual vote has provided, and will continue to provide, valuable feedback on executive compensation. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_38"></A>2016 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> Frequency Advisory Vote
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Unlike the other proposals included on the proxy card, you have four choices as to how to vote on this
proposal. You may cast your vote on your preferred voting frequency by choosing the option of one year, two years or three years or abstain from voting when you vote in response to this proposal. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Your vote on this resolution is an advisory vote. Although the Board is not required to take any action in response to
the stockholder vote, the Board values our stockholders&#146; opinions. As in prior years, the Board intends to consider the results of this vote carefully when making future decisions regarding how often the Company should conduct a stockholder
advisory vote on executive compensation. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_39"></A>Resolution </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We are asking our stockholders to vote on the following resolution: </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:8%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">RESOLVED, that the stockholders indicate, by their vote on this resolution, whether the advisory vote on executive
compensation should be held every one year, every two years or every three years. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_40"></A>Recommendation of the Board
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors unanimously recommends a vote for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Say-on-Pay</FONT></FONT> votes &#147;<U>EVERY YEAR</U>&#148;.</B> </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-25-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_41"></A>EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_42"></A>COMPENSATION DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_43"></A>Executive Summary </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This
Compensation Discussion and Analysis describes the overall approach to the Company&#146;s executive compensation policies and practices for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, with a specific focus on the compensation program for our named
executive officers, or &#147;NEOs&#148;: Daniel Coleman, Steffen Parratt, Philip Allison, Ryan Primmer, Greg Tusar and Jonathan Ross. Although Mr.&nbsp;Ross ceased providing services to the Company in September 2016, he is considered an NEO for
fiscal year 2016 pursuant to the SEC&#146;s rules regarding proxy disclosure. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In 2016, KCG continued to
distinguish itself as an emerging, independent, pure-play, technology-driven intermediary in liquid financial instruments. KCG&#146;s long-term growth is aligned with profound, secular changes in technology, regulation and competition and the
Company is focused on attaining scale to enable it to grow without creating significant costs. As part of these efforts, in 2016, KCG undertook a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">re-engineering</FONT> of the firm&#146;s trading architecture while
managing revenues in a difficult operating environment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For the 2016 performance year, the individual and
firm-wide performance metrics used by the Compensation Committee to make annual incentive compensation decisions were designed to focus management on the Company&#146;s strategic objectives for 2016. Specifically, the portion of the NEOs&#146; 2016
annual incentive award based on the achievement of Company financial performance goals (the &#147;Performance Portion&#148;) was tied to a combination of consolidated earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization
(&#147;EBITDA&#148;) and return on equity. Separately, the Compensation Committee rebalanced the weighting of the Performance Portion and the portion of the 2016 annual incentive award based on the achievement of individual initiatives (the
&#147;Initiatives Portion&#148;) for each of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, so that a greater percentage of Messrs. Coleman&#146;s and Parratt&#146;s award determination for 2016 was tied to achievement of Company financial performance goals.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">KCG believes these changes illustrate the Company&#146;s commitment to paying for performance, one of our
core compensation philosophies, because the addition of the return on equity metric for our NEOs and the increased weighting of the Performance Portion for Messrs. Coleman and Parratt will continue to motivate our management team to execute on the
Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives, which, as a result, will deliver value to our stockholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>Executive Compensation Program</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="8"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="2"></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ROWSPAN="4"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No tax
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-ups</FONT> for perquisites</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No single-trigger change in control benefits</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-ups</FONT> on severance
payments</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Recoupment of cash incentive and equity awards from executive officers
in the event of certain financial statement restatements and other events</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" ROWSPAN="4"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Annual reviews of our executive
compensation program by our Compensation Committee</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No stock options with exercise price below market</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No repricing of underwater stock options</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:4.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;No
excessive perquisites or benefits</FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_44"></A>2016 Compensation Program Highlights </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As a result of ongoing discussions with our Board, the Compensation Committee implemented the following changes to the
Company&#146;s annual incentive award program for 2016. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Performance Metric Alignment &#150; Return on Equity.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Similar to the metrics used for the Performance Portion
of the annual incentive award for Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, for purposes of 2016 annual incentive award determinations for each of Messrs. Allison, Primmer and Tusar, return on equity replaced the component of the Performance Portion previously
tied to business unit measures. The Compensation Committee believed that using the return on equity metric as a key component of 2016 annual incentive award determinations was appropriate in light of the Company&#146;s focus on achieving a
double-digit return on equity. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Increased Performance Portion Weighting.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For 2016, the Compensation Committee rebalanced the weighting of the
Performance and Initiatives Portions of the 2016 annual incentive award for each of Messrs. Coleman and Parratt, so that as compared to 2015, a greater percentage of Messrs. Coleman&#146;s and Parratt&#146;s award determination for 2016 was tied to
Company financial performance goals including return on equity and EBITDA, with a lesser percentage based on the Initiatives Portion. An increased weighting of the Performance Portion for Messrs. Coleman and Parratt is consistent with our core
compensation philosophy of paying for performance, and will continue to motivate our management team to execute on the Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives, which, as a result, will deliver value to our stockholders.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_45"></A>COMPENSATION DECISION-MAKING PROCESS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_46"></A>Compensation Philosophy </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee believes KCG&#146;s compensation programs should support its business strategies and provide balanced incentives for achieving short-term and long-term business goals and
objectives. KCG designs compensation packages that are intended to align the long-term economic interests of KCG&#146;s executive officers with its stockholders&#146; interests while also providing appropriate awards to motivate superior individual
performance. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In making compensation decisions, the Compensation Committee utilizes the following principles
to ensure that our compensation structure is competitive and reflects our core values: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Pay for performance.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Provide a compensation framework that appropriately awards achievement of the
Company&#146;s financial and strategic objectives and supports the attainment of KCG&#146;s vision, business strategy and operating imperatives, while reinforcing KCG&#146;s business values and creating value over the long term.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Align compensation with stockholders&#146; interests.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Motivate management to achieve financial and strategic
goals by delivering a meaningful portion of incentive compensation in equity awards, which aligns employee interests with those of stockholders. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-27-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Mitigate excessive risk-taking.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Ensure that our incentive compensation arrangements do not encourage our
employees to take unnecessary and excessive risks, including risks that threaten the value of the Company. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Attract and retain a talented leadership team.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Design an incentive compensation program that allows the Company
to attract and retain qualified employees, for whom competition is diverse and includes a variety of financial services and technology firms. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_47"></A>Key Compensation Practices </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In
addition to aligning executive pay with long-term stockholder interests, we are committed to good corporate governance practices and mitigation of inappropriate risk-taking. To further this commitment, our 2016 compensation program had the following
features: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Long-term ownership.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As discussed below under &#147;KCG Compensation Decisions for 2016&#151;Long-Term Equity
Incentives,&#148; we continued our practice of delivering a meaningful portion of the 2016 annual incentive award in the form of equity. For 2016, our named executive officers (other than Messrs. Coleman and Ross) were granted RSUs that are subject
to market, cancellation and forfeiture risk over a multi-year period. Separately, in connection with the execution of his amended and rested employment agreement in April 2016, Mr.&nbsp;Coleman was granted Performance Options which are designed to
deliver value only if the Company stock price increases above $23.35 (the exercise price of such award). The terms of Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s amended and restated employment agreement are described under &#147;Agreements with Our Named Executive
Officers&#151;Employment Agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Coleman,&#148; below. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Recoupment and forfeiture policies.</I></B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our named executive officers are subject to recoupment policies that
provide for the cancellation or clawback of cash incentive and equity awards in the event of, among other things, fraud and financial restatement. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Continued review of compensation program.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B>Each year, our Compensation Committee reviews our compensation
program to ensure that executive pay is aligned with Company policies, long-term stockholder interests and sound risk policies. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_48"></A>Compensation Committee Role and Responsibility </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee determines each continuing named executive officer&#146;s compensation package in accordance with the terms of the named executive officer&#146;s employment agreement on an
annual basis and at times of promotions or other changes in responsibilities. The Compensation Committee may review market data, such as pay data from proxy statements and other sources, as a reference point for evaluating the relative
competitiveness of the compensation packages offered to the named executive officers. The Compensation Committee has also retained Pay Governance to act as its compensation consultant on an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">as-needed</FONT> basis.
From time to time, the Compensation Committee receives advice and guidance from Pay Governance on executive compensation matters and, with respect to named executive officers other than the CEO, considers recommendations from the CEO. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In making compensation decisions for the targeted total compensation opportunity for each of the named executive
officers, the Compensation Committee considers each element of each named executive officer&#146;s compensation package and the total compensation that the named executive officer may be eligible to receive. Multiple factors may be considered in
determining the amount of total compensation to award the named executive officers each year. These factors may include: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="9%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the present and future value of any equity-based awards that are granted during the year; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">alignment of short-term and long-term performance of KCG with variable elements of targeted total compensation; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">internal pay equity considerations; and </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">the relative competitiveness of KCG&#146;s compensation packages to the market generally. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
