<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_49"></A>Risk </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As described in the Compensation and Risk section of this Proxy Statement, our Compensation Committee believes that the
mitigation of excessive risk-taking is an important component of the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy, and it reviews our compensation plans, including the plans in which each of our named executive officers and other members of our management
committee participate, with this objective in mind. Given the risk-mitigating controls such as the Equity Incentive Plan&#146;s recapture and cancellation provisions and our Compensation Recoupment Policy and other factors such as the balance of
fixed and discretionary compensation and short-term and long-term incentives, we believe that our compensation plans, arrangements and agreements with the named executive officers are well balanced and structured in a manner that does not encourage
imprudent risk-taking that could threaten the Company&#146;s value. The Compensation Committee believes that the Company&#146;s compensation framework aligns with sound risk management and that the Company&#146;s compensation plans, policies and
practices do not encourage excessive risk taking that is reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_50">
</A>Role of Compensation Consultants </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Pay Governance was originally engaged to assist with establishing the
Company&#146;s compensation programs after the closing of the Mergers and continues to advise the Compensation Committee as needed on developing trends and best practices in executive compensation design. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_51"></A>2016 COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_52"></A>Compensation Elements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Below we
discuss 2016 compensation determinations for each of our named executive officers. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_53"></A>Ongoing Compensation
Elements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table outlines the primary components of compensation paid to each of our named
executive officers for the 2016 performance year. </FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Variable compensation designed to reward the achievement of
annual financial and other corporate performance goals and personal performance</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<I>Performance Portion</I>:<B>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</B>Earned based on the
achievement of objective Company financial performance goals established by the Compensation Committee</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3.50em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>75% </B>weighting<B> </B>for CEO and CFO</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3.50em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>67% </B>weighting<B> </B>for other NEOs</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<I>Initiatives Portion</I>:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Earned based on the achievement
of individual initiatives established by the Compensation Committee in consultation with our CEO</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3.50em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>25% </B>weighting<B> </B>for CEO and CFO</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:3.50em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>33% </B>weighting<B> </B>for other NEOs</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Earned awards are subject to the Compensation Recoupment
Policy</FONT></P></TD></TR>

Compensation</I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="top"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Annual variable compensation structured to
(1)&nbsp;encourage the achievement of longer-term performance goals, (2)&nbsp;create an ownership culture focused on long-term value creation for KCG&#146;s stockholders and (3)&nbsp;encourage proper risk-taking by balancing the short-term component
of other compensation elements</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>65%</B> of annual incentive compensation payout for CEO</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>50%</B> of annual incentive compensation payout for other NEOs</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Vests over a three-year period; subject to market risk and cancellation and forfeiture provisions under the Equity Incentive Plan and the
Compensation Recoupment Policy</FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="8" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8px" BGCOLOR="#dff6fb">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="8" COLSPAN="4" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="top" COLSPAN="3" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:8px"> <P STYLE="margin-left:1.20em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Cash Component of Annual Incentive
Compensation</I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">

intended to provide executives an annual cash payout linked to Company and individual performance</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" align="left">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px; margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.50em"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#149;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<B>50%</B> of annual incentive compensation payout for other

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_54"></A>Compensation Decisions for 2016 </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Base Salaries </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with the execution of employment agreements with certain members of our management team, the Compensation Committee determined an annual base salary of $500,000 for each of Messrs. Tusar,
Primmer and Ross was appropriate based on competitive market data and each named executive officer&#146;s position and level of responsibilities. At the same time, after reviewing competitive market data from our peer group, compensation survey
data, and large global banks in the context of Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s total compensation package, the Compensation Committee determined that an annual base salary of $1,000,000 was appropriate for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The base salaries of Messrs. Coleman, Tusar and Primmer have not increased from the 2013 rates, and Messrs.
Allison&#146;s and Parratt&#146;s base salaries were similarly established at &pound;350,000 and $500,000, respectively, in connection with the executives&#146; appointments in September 2014 and January 2015, respectively. Using the average of
daily spot rates of $1.35799 to &pound;1 for 2016, Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s annual base salary of &pound;350,000 converts to an annual base salary of $475,296, which is in line with the base salary rate paid to the other members of our management
team (other than Mr.&nbsp;Coleman). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Annual Incentives </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In the first quarter of 2016, the Compensation Committee structured the 2016 annual incentive awards for Messrs. Coleman
and Parratt so that 75% of each executive&#146;s target award was based on the achievement of KCG financial performance goals under the Performance Portion and 25% of the target award was based on the achievement of individual initiatives under the
Initiatives Portion. The Compensation Committee separately structured the 2016 annual incentive awards for each of Messrs. Allison, Primmer and Tusar so that <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> of each executive&#146;s target award
was based on the achievement of KCG financial performance goals under the Performance Portion and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-third</FONT> of the target award was based on the achievement of individual initiatives under the Initiatives
Portion. The potential payout for each executive may not exceed 200% of his respective target award. The table below sets forth the target 2016 annual incentive award for each of our continuing NEOs. </FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s 2016 annual incentive award was determined pursuant to the terms of
his Separation Agreement and as a result, he is not included in this discussion. A description of the payment made to Mr.&nbsp;Ross in respect of his 2016 annual incentive awards is included below under &#147;2016 Annual Incentive Compensation
Determinations&#151;Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#148; on page 35. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Performance Portion</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
Compensation Committee determined to use return on equity (&#147;ROE&#148;) and EBITDA as the metrics for determining the Performance Portion of the executives&#146; 2016 annual incentive award. In each case, the ROE and EBITDA measures were
adjusted to exclude items including, but not limited to: (1)&nbsp;the impact of the sale of Bats; and (2)&nbsp;the impact of the management committee&#146;s annual incentive awards, which exclusion was necessary to avoid the circularity of including
such payments as a component of the target used to determine the achievement of such measure (as adjusted, &#147;Adjusted ROE&#148; and &#147;Adjusted EBITDA,&#148; respectively). Adjusted ROE and Adjusted EBITDA were weighted 33% and 67%,
respectively, for purposes of determining the Performance Portion for Messrs. Coleman and Parratt and such metrics were weighted equally </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-31-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For 2016, the Compensation Committee certified in the first quarter of 2017 that the
Adjusted ROE and Adjusted EBITDA metrics were earned at 11% and 48% of target, respectively (with return on equity on an unadjusted basis earned at 9% of target for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman). In view of the Company&#146;s overall full year results,
Mr.&nbsp;Coleman recommended forgoing his annual incentive payout for 2016 and Mr.&nbsp;Parratt recommended forgoing a portion of his annual incentive payout for 2016. The Compensation Committee accepted Messrs. Coleman&#146;s and Parratt&#146;s
recommendations and commended the executives for their leadership and commitment to the Company&#146;s success over the longer term. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Initiatives Portion</I>.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Initiatives Portion considered the named executive officers&#146; progress toward achieving specific objectives that reflect each officer&#146;s
individual role at KCG, as discussed below. The individual initiatives for Mr.&nbsp;Coleman were established by the Compensation Committee, and the individual initiatives for Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar were established by the
Compensation Committee in consultation with Mr.&nbsp;Coleman. In determining the level of achievement of the Initiatives Portion for Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer, and Tusar, our CEO met with each officer in early 2017 to review actual
performance versus the objectives set under the Initiatives Portion, and then made recommendations to the Compensation Committee based on his performance assessment, which the Compensation Committee considered in determining actual payout of the
annual incentive awards. As noted above, Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s 2016 annual incentive award was determined pursuant to the terms of his Separation Agreement and is described below under &#147;2016 Annual Incentive Compensation
Determinations&#151;Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#148; on page 35. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mr.&nbsp;Coleman </I></FONT></P>

receive an annual incentive award for 2016, the Chairman of the Board of Directors and the Chair of the Compensation Committee reviewed the CEO&#146;s self-performance assessment with respect to his Initiatives

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The level of achievement of the Performance Portion and Incentives Portion
and the aggregate annual incentive award paid to Messrs. Coleman, Allison, Primmer and Tusar are set forth in the table below. If Mr.&nbsp;Coleman had not forgone his 2016 annual incentive award, 65% of such amount would have been delivered in RSUs,
with the remainder paid in cash. The annual incentive awards earned by Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar were paid in equal parts RSUs and cash. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Coleman recommended to the Compensation Committee that he forgo his annual incentive payout for 2016. The Compensation Committee accepted

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Parratt recommended to the Compensation Committee that he forgo a portion of his annual incentive payout for 2016. The Compensation
Committee accepted Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s recommendation and as a result, Mr.&nbsp;Parratt did not receive $56,727 that would have otherwise been payable to him based on actual Performance Portion results. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Long-Term Equity Incentives </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Company believes that long-term equity incentive awards are a key element of the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pay-for-performance</FONT></FONT>
compensation philosophy because they align the interests of our executives with those of our stockholders by subjecting a significant portion of compensation to market risk over a multiple-year period. The RSUs granted to our executives are
inherently performance-based and help to motivate individuals to execute on the Company&#146;s long-term business strategy and to achieve strategic, financial and operational objectives because the value of these equity awards is directly dependent
on the price of our stock. Additionally, equity awards such as our RSUs are an important tool for deferring a substantial portion of compensation, which aids in retention and mitigates inappropriate short-term risk-taking. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In accordance with this component of the Company&#146;s
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pay-for-performance</FONT></FONT> philosophy, the Company continued to award a meaningful portion of the 2016 annual incentive award earned by its executive officers in the form of
equity awards. As noted above, Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar received RSUs in respect of 50% of each executive&#146;s 2016 annual incentive award and if Mr.&nbsp;Coleman had not forgone such award, 65% of his 2016 annual incentive
award would have been granted in the form of RSUs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to being subject to market risk over a
multi-year period, all RSUs granted to our named executive officers are subject to recapture and cancellation provisions under the terms of our Equity Incentive Plan, as well as forfeiture provisions under our Compensation Recoupment Policy. For
more details on the stock options, SARs and RSUs held by our named executive officers, see &#147;Outstanding Equity Awards at Fiscal <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Year-End</FONT> 2016&#148; below. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-34-
</FONT></P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In determining the 2016 annual incentive for Mr.&nbsp;Ross, the Compensation Committee provided him with a cash award of
$1,100,000, which was the minimum award established pursuant to the terms of his Separation Agreement with the Company. This amount was paid to Mr.&nbsp;Ross at the same time such amounts were paid to the other named executive officers, subject to
Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s execution and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-revocation</FONT> of a release of claims. See &#147;Agreements with our Named Executive Officers&#151;Separation Agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#148; on page 44 for a description
of the Separation Agreement entered into with Mr.&nbsp;Ross in connection with his departure from the Company. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_55"></A>Compensation Program Highlights for 2017 </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee routinely reviews and discusses the Company&#146;s compensation programs to ensure that they
support its business strategies and provide balanced incentives for achieving short-term and long-term business goals and objectives. As a result of its ongoing review of the executive compensation programs for 2016 and ongoing discussions with the
Board, the Compensation Committee implemented a plan for the 2017 performance year which is similar to the 2016 program. The Compensation Committee believes use of the ROE and EBITDA metrics as key components of making 2017 annual incentive award
determinations is appropriate as the Company works towards achieving a double-digit return on equity. The weighting of the Performance Portion and Initiatives Portion used for 2017 compensation decisions of our named executive officers will also
remain the same. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_56"></A>OTHER COMPENSATION AND BENEFITS ELEMENTS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Retirement and Benefit Plans </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">KCG provides named executive officers with access to retirement and health and welfare programs, on the same terms and conditions as those made to salaried employees generally. Although the Company
sponsors a </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-35-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
voluntary deferred compensation plan, a legacy Knight arrangement, none of our NEOs currently participates in such plan, nor do any of our NEOs have balances outstanding under such plan.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Perquisites </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Our named executive officers generally are offered perquisites on the same basis as our general employee population. See the &#147;Summary Compensation Table&#148; set forth below for more information.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_57"></A>TAX CONSIDERATIONS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_58"></A>Section 162(m) Tax Considerations </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Generally, Section 162(m) of the Code imposes a $1&nbsp;million limit on the amount that a public company may deduct for
compensation paid to its chief executive officer and three other most highly compensated officers, other than the chief financial officer, each year. This limitation does not apply to &#147;qualifying performance-based&#148; compensation as defined
in the Code. The Compensation Committee has and will continue to emphasize performance-based compensation for the named executive officers and will seek to minimize the impact of Section 162(m); however, the Compensation Committee may not
necessarily limit executive compensation to the amount deductible under Section 162(m) of the Code. In certain situations, the Compensation Committee may approve compensation that will not be deductible in order to ensure competitive levels of total
compensation for the named executive officers or for other reasons. Although the Compensation Committee determined that a portion of named executive officer compensation for 2016 would be <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-deductible</FONT> to the
Company under Section 162(m) of the Code, it approved payment of annual incentive awards based on actual Performance Portion and Individual Portion results, recognizing that the management team had executed on certain strategic accomplishments over
the course of the year and that the potential loss of deduction would not be material. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_59"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE REPORT </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Compensation Committee, composed of independent directors, reviewed and discussed the above &#147;Compensation
Discussion and Analysis&#148; with KCG&#146;s management. Based on the review and its discussions, the Compensation Committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; be included in this Proxy
Statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Compensation Committee, members as of</I> </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>December&nbsp;31, 2016</I> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:54%; text-indent:-2%"><FONT

officer) for 2016, as well as one of our most highly compensated executive officers who was not serving as an executive officer at the end of 2016. In accordance with SEC rules, the following table includes summary compensation information for 2015
and 2014 if the executive officer was included in KCG&#146;s Summary Compensation Table for either of those years. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

Allison&#146;s, Primmer&#146;s and Tusar&#146;s performance during 2015. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">One-third</FONT> of such RSU awards vested on February&nbsp;3, 2017 and the remainder will vest in equal installments on February&nbsp;3, 2018
and February&nbsp;3, 2019. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">(4)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">These Performance Options, which have an exercise price of $23.35, were granted to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman in connection with the amendment and restatement
of his employment agreement as described in &#147;Agreements with Our Named Executive Officers&#151;Employment Agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Coleman,&#148; below. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">One-third</FONT> of the Performance Options vested on
December&nbsp;31, 2016 and the remainder will vest in equal installments on each of December&nbsp;31, 2017 and December&nbsp;31, 2018. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Includes a special <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-time</FONT> award of 47,620 RSUs granted at the same time as the grant of the equity
component of the 2015 annual incentive award, as described in (3)&nbsp;above. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">One-third</FONT> of Mr.&nbsp;Primmer&#146;s special <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-time</FONT> award of RSUs vested on
February&nbsp;3, 2017 and the remainder will vest in equal installments on February&nbsp;3, 2018 and February&nbsp;3, 2019, subject to his continued employment with KCG. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_65"></A>AGREEMENTS WITH OUR NAMED EXECUTIVE OFFICERS </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_66"></A>Agreements with Mr.&nbsp;Coleman </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On April&nbsp;21, 2016, the Company and Mr.&nbsp;Coleman entered into an amended and restated employment agreement (the
&#147;Employment Agreement&#148;), which amended and restated the previous employment agreement between KCG and Mr.&nbsp;Coleman, dated as of July&nbsp;1, 2013. Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s Employment Agreement provides for his employment as Chief
Executive Officer of KCG for a term beginning on April&nbsp;21, 2016 and ending on December&nbsp;31, 2018. During the term, the Board will continue to nominate Mr.&nbsp;Coleman to serve as a member of the Board unless prohibited by applicable law.
Following the term, Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be available to consult on transition matters and to provide general advisory services to the Company, as may be reasonably requested by the Company from time to time, provided that in no event will
Mr.&nbsp;Coleman provide more than 200 hours of such services over the duration of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> period described below, nor will Mr.&nbsp;Coleman receive any compensation in consideration for providing
such advisory services. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Employment Agreement provides for, among other things: (1)&nbsp;that
Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will continue to receive an annual base salary of $1,000,000; (2)&nbsp;that Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be eligible for an annual incentive award for the 2016 calendar year delivered 65% in restricted stock units and 35% in cash, with a
target of $7,000,000 and a maximum of $14,000,000 and (3)&nbsp;the grant of 2,000,000 performance stock options with an exercise price of the greater of the fair market value on the date of grant and $23.35 (the &#147;Performance Options&#148;). The
Performance Options have a five-year term, are subject to certain exceptions set forth in the Employment Agreement, and will vest in three equal installments on each of December&nbsp;31, 2016, December&nbsp;31, 2017 and December&nbsp;31, 2018,
subject to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s continued employment with KCG. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be subject to a
covenant not to compete with KCG or its affiliates during his employment and for a period of 12 months following his termination for any reason and to a covenant not to solicit employees during his employment and for a period of 36 months following
his termination for any reason. If Mr.&nbsp;Coleman breaches the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants, he must forfeit all unexercised Performance Options
(whether vested or unvested) and repay to KCG any gains that he received after the end of his employment from the exercise of Performance Options and from the vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity. Following a &#147;change in
control&#148; (as defined in the Employment Agreement), each of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> period and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> period will be reduced to six months following his
termination without &#147;cause&#148; or a termination with &#147;good reason&#148;. Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s obligation to comply with the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants survives the end of the term of the Employment Agreement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">If Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s employment is terminated during the term of the Employment Agreement by KCG without &#147;cause&#148; or by Mr.&nbsp;Coleman for &#147;good reason&#148; (each as defined in the
Employment Agreement), subject to his execution of a release, Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be entitled to receive: (1)&nbsp;subject to compliance with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants described above, (A)&nbsp;continued vesting of his Performance Options (which will remain exercisable until they expire at the completion of their five-year term), (B)&nbsp;continued
vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity, and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(C)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit</FONT></FONT> payments equal, in the aggregate, to $2,000,000, paid in equal monthly
installments over the course of his <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> period described above; (2)&nbsp;any earned but unpaid annual incentive for the fiscal year ending immediately before termination, paid 100% in cash;
(3)&nbsp;an annual incentive for the fiscal year in which the termination occurs, paid 100% in cash and prorated for the number of days elapsed during the year prior to the termination; and (4)&nbsp;payment of COBRA health insurance premiums for up
to 12 months following termination. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Upon a resignation by Mr.&nbsp;Coleman without &#147;good reason&#148;,
during the term of the Employment Agreement: (1)&nbsp;subject to his execution of a release and his compliance with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants
described above, (A)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s vested Performance Options will remain exercisable until they expire at the completion of their five-year term, (B)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Coleman&#146;s annual incentive paid in the form of equity that was
earned during the term will continue to vest and (C)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will be entitled to receive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">the&nbsp;non-compete/</FONT></FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-42-
</FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicit</FONT> payments described above, and (2)&nbsp;Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will forfeit any unpaid annual incentives and any unvested Performance Options.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On April&nbsp;17, 2014, KCG and Redmont Holdings LLC entered into an amended Aircraft Timesharing Agreement
under which Mr.&nbsp;Coleman will lease and operate his personal aircraft on behalf of KCG on a nonexclusive basis. KCG has agreed to reimburse Mr.&nbsp;Coleman at the rate of $5,000 per flight hour for use of his aircraft by employees of KCG,
provided that such amount does not exceed the maximum amount permitted to be charged under Section 91.501(d) of the Federal Aviation Regulations, in which event the charge will be less. The amount charged in any single year may not exceed $125,000
without the general approval of the Board. During 2016, there was no use of the aircraft by employees of KCG and accordingly, KCG was not required to make any reimbursement payments to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman. The Aircraft Timesharing Agreement has an
initial term of one year and will continue for additional periods of one year unless terminated by either party on 30 days&#146; written notice. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_67"></A>Employment Agreements with Messrs. Parratt, Allison, Primmer and Tusar </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mr.&nbsp;Parratt </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with his January 2015
appointment as Chief Financial Officer, the Compensation Committee approved, and authorized the Company to enter into, an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Parratt. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s employment agreement has an initial term of three years and
thereafter renews automatically for successive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> extension terms unless either party gives notice of nonrenewal at least 90 days before the end of the applicable term. Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s employment
agreement provides for, among other things: (i)&nbsp;an initial annual base salary of $500,000, (ii) an annual incentive award, (iii)&nbsp;a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">sign-on</FONT> award of $500,000 granted in the form of RSUs that vest in
three equal installments on each of the first three anniversaries of the date of grant, subject to Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s continued employment with KCG and (iv)&nbsp;a 2015 annual incentive award no less than 200% of the amount of
Mr.&nbsp;Parratt&#146;s base salary. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Parratt is subject to a covenant not to compete with KCG or its
affiliates during his employment and for a period of six months thereafter and to a covenant not to solicit KCG&#146;s employees during his employment and for a period of 18 months following his termination of employment for any reason. If
Mr.&nbsp;Parratt is terminated by KCG without cause or by reason of his resignation for good reason (each as defined in the employment agreements), subject to the execution of a release, Mr.&nbsp;Parratt will be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;subject
to compliance with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants described above, (a)&nbsp;continued vesting of his <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">sign-on</FONT>
award of RSUs, (b)&nbsp;continued vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(c)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit</FONT></FONT> payments equal, in the aggregate, to
$500,000, paid in equal monthly installments over the course of his <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> period described above; (ii)&nbsp;any earned but unpaid annual incentive for the fiscal year ending immediately before
termination, paid 100% in cash; (iii)&nbsp;an annual incentive for the fiscal year in which the termination occurs, paid 100% in cash and prorated for the number of days elapsed during the year; and (iv)&nbsp;payment of COBRA health insurance
premiums for up to 12 months following termination. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Mr.&nbsp;Allison </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In connection with his appointment as Chief Executive Officer of KCG Europe, Mr.&nbsp;Allison and KCG Europe entered into
an employment agreement, pursuant to which Mr.&nbsp;Allison commenced employment with KCG Europe effective September&nbsp;22, 2014. The employment agreement does not have a set term, but stipulates that Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment with KCG
Europe will continue as per the terms of the employment agreement until either party gives written notice of termination at least six months prior to the effective date of such termination. However, KCG Europe may, at its discretion, terminate
Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment with immediate effect and pay Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s base salary over the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">six-month</FONT> period in lieu of giving advance notice of such termination. Additionally, KCG Europe may
terminate Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment without notice and without any payment in lieu of notice if Mr.&nbsp;Allison is guilty of gross misconduct. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment agreement provides for, among other things: (i)&nbsp;an initial annual base salary of &pound;350,000; (ii) subject to Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s employment in good standing
through January&nbsp;31, 2015, a payment equal </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-43-
</FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
to $2,000,000 less the amount of base salary received in 2014, paid 60% in the form of KCG equity and 40% in cash (the &#147;2014 Compensation Payment&#148;); and (iii)&nbsp;the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-time</FONT> award of 750,000 Replacement RSUs, which was granted to Mr.&nbsp;Allison after he provided KCG with satisfactory documentation showing that he forfeited equity awards granted by his previous employer in
connection with his resignation of employment with such prior employer to join KCG. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">One-third</FONT> of the Replacement RSUs vested on each of July&nbsp;1, 2015, September&nbsp;22, 2015 and September&nbsp;22, 2016.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During the term of his employment and for 12 months thereafter, Mr.&nbsp;Allison is subject to a covenant not
to compete with KCG Europe and a covenant not to solicit customers, potential customers and key employees of KCG Europe; provided, however, that the length of Mr.&nbsp;Allison&#146;s required compliance with these
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants will be reduced by any period of &#147;garden leave&#148; he is required by KCG Europe to serve in connection with a
termination of employment. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Messrs. Primmer and Tusar </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In January 2014, the Company entered into amended and restated employment agreements with each of Messrs. Primmer and
Tusar. The employment agreements have an initial term of three years and thereafter renew automatically for successive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> extension terms unless either party gives notice of nonrenewal at least 90 days
before the end of the applicable term. The employment agreements provide for, among other things: (i)&nbsp;an initial annual base salary of $500,000 (ii) an annual incentive award and (iii)&nbsp;for Mr.&nbsp;Primmer, a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">sign-on</FONT> award of $3,600,000 granted in the form of RSUs that vest in three equal installments on the first three anniversaries of Mr.&nbsp;Primmer&#146;s start date (Mr.&nbsp;Primmer&#146;s &#147;Performance
Award&#148;). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Each of Messrs. Primmer and Tusar is subject to a covenant not to compete with KCG or its
affiliates during his employment and for a period of six months thereafter and to a covenant not to solicit KCG&#146;s employees during his employment and for a period of 18 months following his termination of employment for any reason. If
Mr.&nbsp;Primmer is terminated by KCG without cause or by reason of his resignation for good reason (each as defined in the employment agreements), subject to the execution of a release and to his compliance with
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants described above, he will be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;full vesting of his Performance Awards, (ii)&nbsp;continued
vesting of any annual incentive paid in the form of equity and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(iii)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit</FONT></FONT> payments equal, in the aggregate, to $500,000. If Mr.&nbsp;Tusar is
terminated by KCG without cause or by reason of his resignation for good reason (each as defined in the employment agreements), subject to the execution of a release and to his compliance with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT>
and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants described above, he will be entitled to receive: (i)&nbsp;full vesting of all outstanding equity awards and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(ii)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit</FONT></FONT> payments equal, in the aggregate, to the sum of (a) $500,000 and (b) 75% of the cash portion of the annual incentive award paid in
respect of the fiscal year preceding the fiscal year in which Mr.&nbsp;Tusar&#146;s termination of employment occurs. Additionally, upon a termination by KCG without cause or by reason of resignation for good reason, the employment agreements with
Messrs. Primmer and Tusar entitle each to: (i)&nbsp;any earned but unpaid annual incentive for the fiscal year ending immediately before termination, paid 100% in cash; (ii)&nbsp;an annual incentive for the fiscal year in which the termination
occurs, paid 100% in cash and prorated for the number of days elapsed during the year; and (iii)&nbsp;payment of COBRA health insurance premiums for up to 12 months following termination. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_68"></A>Separation Agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Ross </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">On July&nbsp;20, 2016, KCG entered into a separation agreement (the &#147;Separation Agreement&#148;) outlining the payments and benefits due to Mr.&nbsp;Ross in connection with his resignation, which was
effective September&nbsp;30, 2016. Except as modified by the Separation Agreement, the terms and conditions of Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s prior employment agreement remained in full force and effect. Pursuant to the terms of the Separation Agreement,
Mr.&nbsp;Ross remained eligible to receive an annual incentive award in respect of the 2016 calendar year with a target bonus opportunity of $1,500,000, subject to a minimum of $1,100,000 and his execution (and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-revocation)</FONT> of a release of claims. Under the Separation Agreement, all of Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s 2016 bonus would be </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-44-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
paid in cash at the time such amount would have been paid if his employment had not ended, with the amount of such payment determined by KCG in its sole discretion based on an evaluation of
applicable performance factors and subject to the parameters described above. Consistent with the terms of Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s prior employment agreement with KCG and subject to Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s compliance with
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants for six and 18 months, respectively, the Separation Agreement provided for (1)&nbsp;continued vesting in the RSUs held by
Mr.&nbsp;Ross at the time of his resignation as if his employment with the Company had continued and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(2)&nbsp;non-compete/non-solicit</FONT></FONT> payments in the aggregate of
$1,500,000 paid in equal monthly installments over a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">six-month</FONT> period commencing October&nbsp;1, 2016. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">See &#147;Potential Payments on Termination or Change in Control&#148; below for additional information regarding the payments and benefits made to Mr.&nbsp;Ross in connection with his departure.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_69"></A>POTENTIAL PAYMENTS UPON TERMINATION OR CHANGE IN CONTROL </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">This section describes and quantifies the compensation and benefits to which each NEO would have been entitled under
existing plans, arrangements and agreements upon experiencing a termination of employment on December&nbsp;
31, 2016. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_70"></A>Payments and Benefits Upon a Termination or Change in Control </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Agreements with Our Named Executive Officers </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">As discussed above, the agreements with our named executive officers provide certain payments and benefits on terminations of employment, including, in some cases, continued vesting of equity awards. The
agreements do not provide any &#147;single-trigger&#148; payments or benefits on a change in control. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Under
the terms of his Separation Agreement with the Company, Mr.&nbsp;Ross received certain payments and benefits upon his termination of employment, the delivery of which were contingent on his execution of a general release of claims. The actual
payments and benefits to which Mr.&nbsp;Ross became entitled under the terms of his Separation Agreement are described and quantified in the following narrative, and, consistent with the SEC&#146;s proxy disclosure rules, amounts payable to
Mr.&nbsp;Ross upon other potential triggering events are not reflected in the table below because his employment with the Company terminated prior to December&nbsp;31, 2016. Pursuant to the Separation Agreement, Mr.&nbsp;Ross received an annual
incentive award of $1,100,000 in respect of the 2016 calendar year, paid in cash by the Company at the time such awards were paid to the other named executive officers, generally. Consistent with the terms of Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s prior employment
agreement with KCG and subject to Mr.&nbsp;Ross&#146;s compliance with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants for six and 18 months, respectively, following the
Separation Date, Mr.&nbsp;Ross was eligible to (1)&nbsp;receive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-compete/non-solicit</FONT></FONT> payments of $1,500,000 in the aggregate and (2)&nbsp;continue to vest in the
following RSUs that, as of such time remained unvested: 32,058 RSUs granted in February 2014 in respect of the 2013 annual incentive award, 53,636 RSUs granted in February 2015 in respect of the 2014 annual incentive award and 111,844 RSUs granted
in February 2016 in respect of the 2015 annual incentive award. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Effect of Termination Events or Change in Control on Unvested Equity
Awards </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Equity awards held by our named executive officers as of December&nbsp;31, 2016 are subject to the
terms of the Equity Incentive Plan and are each governed by an award agreement evidencing such award. The award agreements set forth the terms and conditions of the respective award and, among other things, outline the effect of various termination
events on the vesting and delivery of unvested equity awards. Awards outstanding under our Equity Incentive Plan are generally subject to &#147;double trigger&#148; vesting upon a change in control; in the event the employment of an Equity Incentive
Plan participant (including our NEOs) is terminated without &#147;cause&#148; or, if applicable, resigns with &#147;good reason&#148; (as each such term as applicable to our NEOs is defined below) within 12 months following a change in control (a
&#147;Qualifying Change in Control Termination&#148;), the award vests in full. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-45-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Additionally, certain equity awards granted to members of our management
team continue to vest in accordance with the applicable vesting schedule after terminations of employment (excluding for cause terminations and Qualifying Change in Control Terminations). For example, pursuant to the terms of the employment
agreements with each of Messrs. Coleman, Parratt and Primmer, upon a termination by the Company without cause or a termination by the executive for good reason, the equity awards granted to such NEOs as a component of his annual incentive
compensation (for example, RSUs granted to NEOs in February 2015 (for the 2014 performance year), February 2016 (for the 2015 performance year) and January 2017 (for the 2016 performance year)) continue to vest as if such executive&#146;s employment
had continued, subject to compliance with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants for the duration of the applicable restrictive covenant period as described
above under &#147;Agreements with Our Named Executive Officers.&#148; Similarly, in the event each of our named executive officers terminates employment with the Company other than for good reason, RSUs granted to each such executive as a component
of his annual incentive compensation (and in certain cases, special <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-time</FONT> equity awards) will continue to vest as if such executive&#146;s employment had continued, subject to compliance with such <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants for the duration of the applicable restrictive covenant period (or for Mr.&nbsp;Allison, for the duration of the applicable
vesting period). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Applicable Definitions: Cause and Good Reason </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">For the purposes of describing certain termination scenarios, &#147;cause&#148; and &#147;good reason&#148; have the
following definitions: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;Cause&#148; is generally defined in the employment agreements with Messrs.
Coleman, Parratt, Primmer and Tusar to mean a finding by the Board of any of the following: (A)&nbsp;continued and willful failure to perform substantially the executive&#146;s responsibilities, after demand for substantial performance has been
given by the Board, (B)&nbsp;illegal conduct, gross misconduct or gross neglect that caused material financial or reputational harm to the Company, (C)&nbsp;conviction of, or plea of guilty or nolo contendere to, a felony, (D)&nbsp;a material breach
of restrictive covenants in the executive&#146;s employment agreement after notice of, and a reasonable opportunity to cure the breach, (E)&nbsp;expulsion, or subjection to an order permanently or temporarily (more than 90 days) enjoining the
executive, from the securities, investment management or investment banking business or the executive&#146;s disqualification or bar from acting in the capacity contemplated by the executive&#146;s employment agreement by the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority, any national securities exchange or any self-regulatory agency or governmental authority, in each case after all appeals have been exhausted or the executive has admitted to such finding by
consent, unless such expulsion, permanent injunction, disqualification or bar was due to the executive&#146;s engagement in conduct with the recorded authorization of the Board or in good faith, reasonable reliance on the advice of the
Company&#146;s counsel, (F)&nbsp;habitual abuse of narcotics or alcohol, (G)&nbsp;fraud or material dishonesty in connection with the Company&#146;s business, or (H)&nbsp;willful misappropriation of the Company&#146;s funds or property. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The Equity Incentive Plan provides that &#147;Cause&#148; has the meaning set forth in an employment agreement or, in the
case of Mr.&nbsp;Allison, means (A)&nbsp;a felony conviction, (B)&nbsp;the commission of an act of fraud or embezzlement against the Company, (C)&nbsp;willful misconduct or gross negligence materially detrimental to the Company, (D)&nbsp;wrongful
dissemination or use of confidential or proprietary information or (E)&nbsp;the intentional and habitual neglect of duties to the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">&#147;Good Reason&#148; is generally defined in the employment agreements with Messrs. Coleman, Parratt, Primmer and Tusar to mean, without the executive&#146;s written consent, a material breach by the
Company of the executive&#146;s employment agreement or of any other material financial obligation to the executive. For Messrs. Parratt, Primmer and Tusar, &#147;good reason&#148; also includes a material diminution in duties, authority or
responsibilities, for Messrs. Primmer and Tusar, &#147;good reason&#148; includes no longer reporting to Mr.&nbsp;Coleman (or his successor) and the transfer of the executive&#146;s primary work site by more than 50 miles and for Mr.&nbsp;Primmer,
&#147;good reason&#148; includes no longer being a member of the Company&#146;s management committee. In order for a termination to constitute a termination for Good Reason, the executive must provide written notice to the Company of the
</FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-46-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
existence of any event or condition that constitutes Good Reason within 90 days of its existence. Upon receipt of such notice, the Company must be given 30 days to remedy such event or condition
and the executive must terminate employment within 60 days following the last day of the Company&#146;s cure period. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_71">
</A>2016 Table of Potential Payments Upon Termination and Change in Control </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The following table sets forth
the details, on an <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">executive-by-executive</FONT></FONT> basis, of the estimated payments and benefits that would be provided to each named executive officer in the event that the
executive&#146;s employment with KCG is (i)&nbsp;terminated by the Company without cause, (ii)&nbsp;terminated by the executive with good reason, (iii)&nbsp;terminated by the executive without good reason, (iv)&nbsp;terminated by reason of the
executive&#146;s death or disability or (v)&nbsp;terminated by reason of a Qualifying Change in Control Termination, in each case, pursuant to the terms of the employment and other agreements described above (including the Equity Incentive Plan).
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The amounts included in the tables are based on the following assumptions: </FONT></P>

<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">

<TD WIDTH="100%"></TD></TR>


<TR BGCOLOR="#cceeff" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="top" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_73"></A>PROPOSAL 4&#151;RATIFICATION OF THE SELECTION OF
PRICEWATERHOUSECOOPERS LLP</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee has appointed PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP (&#147;PwC&#148;) as our
independent registered public accounting firm for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2017. Additionally, the Board of Directors has ratified the appointment of PwC as our independent registered public accounting firm for the fiscal year ending
December&nbsp;31, 2017 and we are submitting the selection of PwC for stockholder ratification at the Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">We expect that representatives of PwC will be present at the Annual Meeting to respond to appropriate questions, and they will have the opportunity to make a statement if they desire. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Although stockholder action on this matter is not required under our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">By-Laws</FONT> or
our Amended and Restated Certificate of Incorporation, this appointment is being recommended to the stockholders for ratification because we believe it is a matter of good corporate practice. Unless contrary instructions are given, shares
represented by proxies solicited by the Board will be voted &#147;for&#148; the ratification of the selection of PwC as our independent registered public accountants for the year ending December&nbsp;31, 2017. If the selection of PwC is not ratified
by the stockholders, the F&amp;A Committee will reconsider whether or not to retain PwC, but still may retain them. Even if the selection of PwC is ratified, the F&amp;A Committee, in its discretion, may direct the appointment of a different
independent registered public accounting firm at any time during the year if it determines that such a change is in our best interests. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Adoption of this proposal requires the affirmative vote of holders of a majority of the votes present in person or represented by proxy. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors unanimously recommends that you vote &#147;<U>FOR</U>&#148; the ratification of
PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP as our independent registered public accounting firm for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2017. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><I>Notwithstanding anything to the contrary set forth in any of our previous filings under the Securities Act, or the Exchange Act, that incorporated future filings, including this Proxy Statement, the
following section titled &#147;Report of the Finance and Audit Committee&#148; shall not be incorporated by reference into any such filings, except to the extent we specifically incorporate such report by reference therein. </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:24px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B>REPORT OF THE FINANCE AND AUDIT COMMITTEE </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2016, the F&amp;A Committee provided assistance to the Board of Directors in fulfilling its oversight of: (1)&nbsp;the integrity of the financial statements and its risk and control environment;
(2)&nbsp;the qualification of, and relationship with, the independent registered public accounting firm; (3)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s internal audit function; (4)&nbsp;compliance with applicable legal and regulatory requirements; and
(5)&nbsp;compliance with the Company&#146;s Code of Business Conduct and Ethics. The F&amp;A Committee also: (A)&nbsp;reviews and makes recommendations to the Board regarding: (i)&nbsp;any proposed material capital formation plans including planned
issuance of equity securities and debt instruments, and stock repurchase programs; and (ii)&nbsp;certain acquisitions, investments, new business ventures, and divestitures by the Company; and (B)&nbsp;annually reviews and approves the
Company&#146;s: (x)&nbsp;treasury investment policy outlining the general investment objectives of the Company and the specific instruments for which investments are permitted; (y)&nbsp;liquidity risk management policy; and (z)&nbsp;contingency
funding plan. The F&amp;A Committee currently operates under a written charter that was approved by the Board on March&nbsp;29, 2017 (the &#147;Charter&#148;). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2016, the F&amp;A Committee was comprised of three independent Directors (Daniel Schmitt, the Chairman, Alastair Rampell and Laurie Shahon). On March&nbsp;16, 2017, Heather E. Tookes was appointed
to the </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-51-
</FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
F&amp;A Committee. On March&nbsp;29, 2017, the Board determined, in its business judgment, that Mr.&nbsp;Schmitt was considered an &#147;audit committee financial expert&#148; as defined by the
SOX Act. The Board also determined at that time, in its business judgment, that Messrs. Schmitt and Rampell and Ms.&nbsp;Shahon and Ms.&nbsp;Tookes each complied with the applicable independence, experience and financial literacy requirements set
forth by the NYSE, the SOX Act and rules adopted by SEC pursuant to the SOX Act. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Management is responsible
for the financial reporting process, including the system of internal control and the preparation, presentation and integrity of the consolidated financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. The independent
registered public accounting firm is responsible for conducting an independent audit of the financial statements in accordance with generally accepted auditing standards and evaluating the Company&#146;s internal controls, including
management&#146;s assertion of the adequacy of its controls over financial reporting as required by Section&nbsp;404 of the SOX Act. The F&amp;A Committee is responsible for monitoring and reviewing these processes. The F&amp;A Committee relies,
without independent verification, on the information provided to it and on the representations made by management and the independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2016, PwC was the Company&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, as appointed by the F&amp;A
Committee and ratified by the Board of Directors on March&nbsp;30, 2016 and approved by the Company&#146;s stockholders at the 2016 Annual Meeting of Stockholders on May&nbsp;11, 2016. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2016, the F&amp;A Committee received and reviewed the written disclosures and the letter from PwC required by
applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (&#147;PCAOB&#148;) regarding the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s communications with the F&amp;A Committee concerning auditor independence and held
discussions and reviewed with PwC all relationships it has with the Company to determine and satisfy itself regarding PwC&#146;s independence. When considering the independence of PwC, the F&amp;A Committee considered whether PwC&#146;s provision of
services to the Company beyond those rendered in connection with its audit and review of the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements was compatible with maintaining its objectivity and independence. The F&amp;A Committee reviewed and
approved, among other matters, the engagement of PwC for audit and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services, and the amount of fees authorized for such services. All <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services
performed by PwC were required to be <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> by the F&amp;A Committee or a specified member thereof. The F&amp;A Committee also evaluated the qualifications and performance of PwC. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In performing its duties, the F&amp;A Committee held six (6)&nbsp;meetings during 2016. The F&amp;A Committee also met in
executive session during regularly scheduled and special meetings held during 2016. At each of its regularly scheduled meetings, the F&amp;A Committee held a joint meeting with the Company&#146;s Risk&nbsp;&amp; Technology Committee to discuss
matters relating to the overlap between risk and internal control functions. Additionally, the F&amp;A Committee met in private session with the Chief Executive Officer, Chief Financial Officer, General Counsel, Chief Risk Officer, Director of
Internal Audit and PwC during various meetings held during 2016. These meetings were designed, among other things, to encourage free and open communications among the F&amp;A Committee, management and PwC. PwC had free access to the F&amp;A
Committee to discuss any matters it deems appropriate. The F&amp;A Committee has discussed with PwC, with and without management present, the overall scope and plan for its annual audit, the results of its examination and the overall quality of the
Company&#146;s financial reporting and its evaluation of the Company&#146;s internal controls, including its assessment on management&#146;s assertion of the adequacy of its controls over financial reporting as required by Section&nbsp;404 of the
SOX Act. Additionally, the F&amp;A Committee discussed matters related to the conduct of the audit and other matters required to be discussed by PCAOB AU &#167;380 (Communication with Audit Committees). The F&amp;A Committee also reviewed and
discussed the Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K,</FONT> the audited consolidated financial statements included therein for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, and Management&#146;s Report on Internal Control over Financial
Reporting with management and PwC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">During 2016, the F&amp;A Committee performed all of its duties and
responsibilities under the Charter. In addition, based on the F&amp;A Committee&#146;s discussions with management and PwC, review of the representations </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">-52-
</FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">
of management, including Management&#146;s Report on Internal Control over Financial Reporting, and the report of PwC to the Board of Directors, and subject to the limitations on the role of the
F&amp;A Committee referred to above and in the Charter, the F&amp;A Committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the Company&#146;s audited consolidated financial statements for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 be included in the
Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K.</FONT> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><I>Finance and Audit Committee, members as
of December&nbsp;31, 2016 </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">Daniel F. Schmitt, Chairman </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="center"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="toc322410_74"></A>AUDIT FEES, AUDIT-RELATED FEES, TAX FEES AND ALL OTHER FEES
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee appointed PwC as our independent registered public accounting firm for the year
ending December&nbsp;31, 2017. We have been advised by PwC that it is an independent public accounting firm registered with the PCAOB and complies with the auditing, quality control and independence standards and rules of the PCAOB and the SEC.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">The F&amp;A Committee also appointed PwC as our independent registered public accounting firm for 2016.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:4%" ALIGN="justify"><FONT STYLE="font-family:Times New Roman" SIZE="2">In addition to retaining PwC to audit the consolidated financial statements for 2016, we retained PwC, as
well as other accounting and consulting firms, to provide various consulting services in 2016, and we expect to continue to do so in the future. We understand the need for PwC to maintain its objectivity and independence in its audit of our
financial statements, and therefore, we do not engage PwC for strategic consulting services, development of tax planning transactions or for services prohibited by the SEC, such as internal audit work and financial information system design and
implementation. We engage PwC for services outside of auditing financial statements when we conclude that (i)&nbsp;PwC is the most appropriate provider of the relevant service and (ii)&nbsp;providing such service is not incompatible with PwC&#146;s
maintenance of objectivity and independence. The following table reflects the fees earned by PwC for services provided to KCG during 2015 and 2016: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
